VESICULAR STOMATITIS, HUMAN - USA (COLORADO) (05)
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Vesicular stomatitis, human - USA (Colorado) 971107230655
Vesicular stomatitis, human - USA (Colorado) (02) 971110181835
Vesicular stomatitis, human: not - USA (Colorado) (03) 971115004414
Vesicular stomatitis, human: not - USA (Colorado) (04) 971115084927
Date: Thu, 13 Nov 1997 10:29:42 -0600
From: Robert B. Tesh <rtesh@utmb.edu>

A recent ProMED posting (11 Nov. 1997) [citation 02 above from Geoff
Letchworth pointed out that human infection with vesicular stomatitis (VS)
serogroup viruses (members of genus _Vesiculovirus_) is not uncommon among
veterinarians, animal handlers and laboratory personnel having contact with
sick livestock or infected laboratory materials. It is important to remind
readers that serological surveys done among human populations living in
rural areas of tropical America and Central Asia indicate that many other
people are also infected with VSV group viruses. Most of these people have
no history of contact with infected animals or laboratory exposure to the
viruses. The mechanism of their infection or of virus transmission is
uncertain, although biting insects have been implicated. Furthermore,
infection with VS group viruses is not always benign. At least two cases
of severe encephalitis due to VS group viruses (VS Indiana and Chandipura)
have been reported in children. For those interested in reading more on
the subject, the following references are recommended:
1) Bhatt, P.N. and Rodrigues, F.M. (1967). Chandipura: A new arbovirus
isolated in India from patients with febrile illness. Ind. J. Med. Res.,
55: 1295-1305.
2) Tesh, R.B., Peralta, P.H., and Johnson, K.M. (1969). Ecologic studies
of vesicular stomatitis virus. 1. Prevalence of infection among animals
and humans living in an area of endemic VSV activity. Am. J. Epidemiol.,
90: 255-261.
3) Pinheiro, F.P., Bensabath, G., Andrade, A.H.P., Lins, Z.C., Fraiha, H.,
Tang, A.T., Lainson, R., Shaw, J.J., and Azevedo, M.C. (1974). Infectious
diseases along Brazil's Trans-Amazon highway: Surveillance and research.
PAHO Bull., 8: 111-122.
4) Cline, B.L. (1976). Ecological associations of vesicular stomatitis
virus in rural Central America and Panama. Am. J. Trop. Med. Hyg., 25:
875-883.
5) Tesh, R., Saidi, S., Javadian, E., Loh, P., and Nadim, A. (1977).
Isfahan virus, a new vesiculovirus infecting humans, gerbils, and sand
flies in Iran. Am. J. Trop. Med. Hyg., 26: 299-306.
6) Gaidamovich, S.Y., Obukhova, V.R., Sveshnikova, N.A., Cherednichenko,
Yu.N., Kostyukov, M.A., Skofertsa, P.G., Yarovoi, P.I., Kurakhmedova, S.A.,
Khanmodefoc, N.M., and Ismailov, A.S. (1978). Natural foci of viruses
transmitted by Phlebotomus papatasi from data on serological investigation
of human populations. Vop. Virus., 5: 556-560 (In Russian).
7) Calisher, C.H., Monath, T.P., Sabattini, M.S., Mitchell, C.J., Lazuick,
J.S., Tesh, R.B., and Cropp, C.B. (1987). A newly recognized
vesiculovirus, Calchaqui virus, and subtypes of Melao and Maguari viruses
from Argentina, with serologic evidence for infections of humans and
horses. Am. J. Trop. Med. Hyg., 36: 114-119.
8) Tesh, R.B., Boshell, J., Modi, G., Morales, A., Young, D.G., Corredor,
A., Ferro, C., de Rodriguez, C., Walters, L.L., Gaitan, M. (1987). Natural
infection of humans, animals and phlebotomine sand flies with the Alagoas
serotype of vesicular stomatitis virus in Colombia. Am. J. Trop. Med.
Hyg., 36:653-661.
9) Rodrigues, J.J., Singh, P.B., Dave, D.S., Prasan, R., Ayachit, V.,
Shaikh, B.H., and Pavri, K.M. (1983). Isolation of Chandipura virus from
the blood in acute encephalopathy syndrome. Ind. J. Med. Res. 77:303-307.
10) Quiroz, E., Moreno, N., Peralta, P.H., and Tesh, R.B. (1988). A
human case of encephalitis associated with vesicular stomatitis virus
(Indiana serotype) infection. Am. J. Trop. Med. Hyg. 39: 312-314.
